The Model-View-Controller (MVC) pattern is a widely used architectural pattern in software development that separates an application into three interconnected components.

### Model

The Model represents the data and business logic of the application. It is responsible for managing the data and performing calculations.

### View

The View is responsible for rendering the user interface and displaying the data to the user. It receives data from the Model and updates the user interface accordingly.

### Controller

The Controller acts as an intermediary between the Model and View. It receives input from the user, updates the Model, and notifies the View to update the user interface.

